{
  "text": "Burning cooking fuels is a major source of indoor air pollution in low-and middle-income countries. Approximately one-half of the world's population uses some form of biomass for cooking. Biomass sources have been implicated in adverse health effects for children (e.g., pneumonia and other acute respiratory infections) in low-and middle-income countries [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Kerosene is more commonly used than wood in the present study site, but exposure to this source may damage lung function and increase the risk of infectious diseases [CITATION_8] . The non-significant association between children's respiratory status and energy types evaluated in this study was consistent with an earlier study in the Czech Republic, which is considered a high income country [CITATION_9] . In the current study, 78.1% of the households opened the windows while cooking, but there was no significant difference in children's respiratory symptoms between households with or without opened windows (p = 0.30). Opened windows are quite common in Indonesia due to its tropical climate where toxic fumes from burning wood or kerosene may be diluted by natural ventilation. However, it should be noted here that the PM measurements were conducted during the early dry season in Sulawesi.",
